I never knew what to do until I just gave in and rolled with it

That wasn’t the case for everything but it got the momentum going, one of these momentous moments hit me last night.

I’ve been in a surplus about a year and a half now. Thinking constantly that I should stay in it and that I’d be happy as long as I knew that I wouldn’t be shrinking.

Currently burning my legs on a cycling bike for some cardio I decided to start last night. I realized it wasn’t benefitting me to stay in a mindset of any ounce of cardio I did that Id lose muscle tissue I’ve worked years for.

Cheers to a recomp ✨🥂

#recomp #fatloss #fitnessjourney #musclegirls #leangains #trackingmacros #fitnessmotivation #gymgirl

Heading into week two of my recomp & how it went:

- I am 1 whole pound lighter, my goal isn’t to lose a large amount of weight but this can happen from time to time, I’ll be looking to stay in a certain weight range for the next 11 weeks and make adjustments if need be.

- I missed 1 cardio session because it truly slipped my mind, I’m in no rush so I’m sticking to my goal of 4 sessions a week & not making up for last week.

- My macros were off 1 day, went over to a friends house and reserved my fats as best as possible but knowing the variance I still considered my macros not hit.

- I’m really digging my new training at the moment, I haven’t felt a large lactic acid pump/burn in awhile, my pain threshold for that training stimulus is very low 😅.

- I’ll be running it for 3 weeks then will move on to a lower rep range with longer rest periods to push more weight & a greater amount of intensity; progressive overload at its finest & my favorite. 😈

How long have you been on your current recomp/fat-loss/building phase?!

3 months ago on this day I was dead set on continuing a bulk/building phase and I didn’t anticipate that today I’d be eating a whole 500 less calories now.

The goal isn’t to lose a drastic amount of weight or get unrealistically lean in a short time frame. It was to improve my relationship with food and along the way see a slightly tighter physique.

I got extremely uninterested with the thought of eating another meal to meet the previous surplus goals. I realized that even some of my favorite meals when eating out were hard to finish and I wasn’t really enjoying them because I  thought of how much MORE I needed to eat.

I just got to a point where I knew that I’ve been in a surplus for a year + and it wasn’t going to be a negative if I reduced my intake, which would help me be more excited for a meal again.

Now, I’m excited to actually cook, can finish a full meal easily, I’m excited to try different meals to match my current intake, and I am actually looking forward to another surplus in the near future. 

Would love to know if you’ve ever had a similar experience! 🤗✨

I got hit with a massive cold a majority of last week and yesterday was my first day back to gym in over a week.

Here’s what I did the day before to ensure I had a positive start back to training: ✨

- I didn’t train the first day I felt 100% better
- focused on getting in a full day’s worth of normal food since my appetite took a hit ⬇️
- didn’t bet on training with a high intensity when I did get back to the gym
- leaned on Essential Defense from Metagenics (amazing to use when you go through any bout of sickness or around someone under the weather) 💊
- I focused on my steps to get some type of activity
- narrowed in on my protein so I knew my body was primed to train & fully recover 🥩
- not get consumed with losing any progress. You get sick, feel better, and there’s nothing more to do than get back to it.

Do I feel flat? Oh yeah 😅
Did I lose some weight? Yes, but nothing that can’t be gained back with consistency

I did have a couple of surprises I wasn’t anticipating with my first training session back:
- I had one of the best leg days I had in awhile 🍑
- I hit a weight for DB RDL’s that I haven’t in over a year
- and I almost felt like like that break in training was needed! 👀

Do you feel anxious about the gym when you get sick or are in full recover mode?!

#fitnessmotivation #fitnessjourney #strengthtraining #health #gymmotivation

A hard truth but one that is extremely attainable for every one of you amazing humans that message 💬 me wanting more muscle, definition, or “tone” if you want to call it that. ⤵️

🫡 You HAVE to set yourself up for success in any exercise you want to push for a new personal best.

 ❌ Performing a large portion of junk volume in the sets leading up to your heaviest is not only doing NOTHING for you but it’s also accumulating fatigue, pre exhausting the muscle, and as a result you’ll have nothing to give!

Keep some reps (and energy) left in the tank on the first 2-3 sets knowing that your all can be put towards your heaviest. 😤

I was not prepared for the dead bugs with resistance 😅☠️

I wanted to add in variations of each exercise for those to start with more beginner friendly or intermediate/advanced core exercises 😈

1. Hanging Knee/Leg Raises (inter/adv) - the 🔑 here is to have some slight tension in your shoulders and avoid hanging as if you were a limp noodle, take it slow
2. SL Crossover Raise (beg) - a bit easier to control but still slow it down!
3. Stability Ball Crunches (inter/adv) - I love the stretch I can achieve before contracting and the lower body stabilizing is just enough of a challenge
4. Ab Mat Crunches (beg) - super easy with the ab mat stationary, think of pressing your mid back down into the padding/floor.
5. Dead Bugs (beg) - you want zero space between your low back and the floor.
6. Dead Bugs w/ resistance (inter/adv) - a lot harder to make sure your lats/arms don’t take over, I think about actively curling my ribs down towards my hips.

Let me know which one you try out!

Round 2 of this growth phase brings a lot of excitement and challenges. I’m genuinely eager to dig deeper every week but I’m also already being confronted with challenges so I wanted to share my experience in hopes that you can realize you’re not alone no matter the goal:

📌 When it comes to increasing calories, it’s easy to think all the added bodyweight will just build up around my mid section. In a growth phase, we have to realize this is a temporary change in our appearance towards the greater goal of increasing muscle mass. Trust the effort you’re putting in.

📌 I’ve had challenges with my relationship with food. I LOVE a good meal, but eating a surplus of calories isn’t always enjoyable, but again it’s something we have to do for the greater goal. An easy way I’m combatting this is to eat more frequent smaller meals so I’m not lethargic after a meal. And honestly, those large meals take forever to eat.

📌 Stress has a tendency to suppress my appetite, making that calorie surplus an even greater challenge. Stress management is huge no mater if you’re in a a deficit or surplus. This can make or break your progress.

📌 It is a daunting task to think about how hard I have to push my training with every session, but in a growth phase its necessary to get a little uncomfortable with the weight you’re adding to the bar.

Every training phase comes with its challenges and we all go through it. It’s important to recognize and log the progress you’ve made. Don’t be afraid of the extra weight you might put on and just visualize the muscle you’re building underneath (because that’s exactly what’s happening 🤝🏼).

Some days I look in the mirror and wish I was leaner, but I can’t get to where I want to be physically without a little discomfort here and there.

Overthinking by is overrated. I used to be extremely hesitant to go on any trip where I couldn’t train. My naive mind at the time would think that I’d lose muscle tissue if I missed a few days in a row. 🫨

Knowing better now here’s what I did: ⤵️

- Hit above my normal step goal, 15-25k daily, easy to do when all you want to do is hike. 🥾😁
- Had premade protein shakes and powder available to make my usual morning smoothie and add some “protein insurance”. 🍇
- Hydrated like a mofo because 90% of the hikes were in 95+ weather and a hydrated muscles are happy muscles. 💧
- Ate snacks/meals conducive to my surplus goal and on the macro friendly side (fruit leather bars, apple sauce, trail mix, granola/protein bars, spaghetti w/ meat sauce, steak & rice, chicken quesadillas, ground turkey burritos) really anything to keep my caloric intake high. 🌯🥪🍝🥩

I knew if I stuck to a few core goals 👆🏼 that my progress wouldn’t be lost. My mind is at ease and hitting a few PR’s before I left made it even easier to take a break. 🏋🏻🏆

You choose to stay consistent but it doesn't mean locking into the same routine come busier times.

With the holiday pressure getting closer and free time getting smaller. Now is the time I start to see more of my client’s to-do lists get longer and the general population throw in the towel and say it’s all too much.

If the soon to be holiday pressure is getting to you and you're not sure how to navigate it, here are some recommendations that will help you keep your progress and still MAKE progress: ⤵️

As life gets busier:
🏋️‍♂️ Adjust from your regular 4-day training to a manageable 3 during the holiday rush. Once the festivities settle, crank it back up to 4.

🏃‍♀️ Can't find time for those 30-minute LISS sessions 3-4 times a week? Give 10 minutes of SIT (Sprint Interval Training) a shot, 3-4 times a week or increase your steps rather than having cardio in place.

🍽️ With holiday feasting on the horizon and potential fluctuations in your food intake, consider shifting from a calorie deficit to maintenance. It not only offers flexibility but also a welcome mental break and more potential for gaining lean muscle mass!

🌬️ As fall sets in and winter in the horizon (even though Texas seems to disagree! 😂), get creative to meet your step goals, even if it means exploring indoor alternatives, bundling up, playing with your dog more, or buying a small foldable treadmill off Amazon.

You're more than capable of making slight adjustments to make training and nutrition more achievable and keep seeing progress that will last you through the holidays, fall, AND winter.

Sometimes doing less or changing your workout routine is exactly what you need to do - if it can help you be more consistent.

✨Remember, it's all about adaptation, not abandonment. ✨

🍖 quads or glutes 🍑
🤷🏻‍♀️You HAVE to know which muscle group you’re training at this point in 2023 and if you’re not sure here’s this 💎 just for you with BSS’s!

➡️ Pro Tip - a bench is easy to find and use BUT if you find it hard to balance on a bench, get a box or riser (even if it’s a couple inches shorter) and use that instead. 

Main takeaways of each variation:

🍑 Glutes 
1)Slight torso lean forward the entire time
2)Your legs should make a 90 degree angle at the lowest point
✨ bonus - you know it’s glute focused when your dumbbells are moving parallel to your shins and some of you might want to have a longer stance to give your legs more space when hinging your hips back

🍖 Quads 
1)Knee flexion forward is KEY, push your knee over your toes as far as you comfortably can, if this is challenging for you then putting a heel wedge under your front foot can help
2)An upright torso will help to bias the quads and your stance is typically smaller than a glute focused bss
✨ bonus - your dumbbells will be moving parallel to your hips or top of your thighs

You don’t want to miss these 👆🏼

1. 20-30g Protein, 30g OR MORE of Carbs, and 5-15g of Fat - the lower the fat in a meal the faster it can digest and be readily available to use as fuel.

2. A dehydrated body = little progress ‼️ at a MINIMUM get at least 9-12 ounces if you’re close to my size. The larger you are, especially when you have more muscle on your frame, the more water you need.

3. Creatine can’t be missed if you’re working towards serious physique goals. Start with 5g daily, don’t skip a day because it takes 2 weeks for Creatine to fully take effect (without a loading phase).

Before you turn to Pilates or yoga for a whole 2 weeks and take out lifting during that time just because you stumbled across “cycle syncing” you have to take your lifestyle, training, and nutrition habits into consideration. ‼️

Are you going to feel stronger, hungrier, more sore, or weaker at different times of your cycle? Of course! But being aware of how to listen👂🏼to your body should be happening 24/7. 

Just like your training and nutrition is ✨individualized✨ to you, so is how you push and pivot your training on your cycle. And by all means when you know you can push GO FOR IT.

When you figure out gaps in your nutrition, consistent with fueling your body, training hard when you can (that’s more often than you think!), recognizing when you’re not recovering (pulling back when needed), and having a proper training program in place this “auto-regulating” or becoming more in tune with your body you WILL see more progress!

Not because you completely took out lifting for 2 weeks but because you are more in tune with what you are capable of!
